[SourceTitle "01 Ruy Lopez Introduction"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-masterclass-edition/course/3489, variation/114753"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The main idea behind Bb5 is to put pressure on 
Black's e5 pawn by attacking the e5-pawn's key defender, the knight on c6. Over 
time, it has evolved as the most critical way to play for White against 2...Nc6. 
9 out of 10 grandmasters prefer the Ruy Lopez over the Italian Game.} *

[Event "Ruy Lopez: Masterclass Edition"]
[Site "Closed Spanish- Chigorin Variation"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Closed Spanish Introduction"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 Closed Spanish- Chigorin Variation"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-masterclass-edition/course/3489, variation/114776"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 {Black begins by kicking away the bishop with 
3...a6} 4. Ba4 Nf6 {Black continues his development.} 5. O-O {White castles and 
allows Black to make a choice. Be7 heads towards a Closed Spanish Structure 
while Nxe4 would lead to a more open position.} Be7 {Black places the bishop on 
e7, threatening Nxe4.} 6. Re1 {White guards the pawn with his rook.} b5 {Black 
plays b5 to stop Bxc6 followed by Nxe5 ideas.} 7. Bb3 {The bishop retreats to 
b3.} d6 {7...d6 leads to the Closed Spanish. The alternative is 7...O-O, which 
can either transpose back to a Closed Spanish or become a Marshall Attack.} 8. 
c3 {White prepares to play d4 and creates a square on c2 for his bishop in case 
Black tries to play Na5.} O-O 9. h3 {White prevents the annoying Bg4. Now we 
have arrived in the starting position of the Closed Spanish. Here Black will 
usually choose from Na5, Nb8, or Bb7, all of which are covered in this 
repertoire. White's play in the Closed Spanish is centered around a stronger 
center and undermining Black's extended queenside pawns with moves such as a4 in 
the future.} *

[Event "Ruy Lopez: Masterclass Edition"]
[Site "Closed Spanish- Chigorin Variation"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Closed Spanish-"]
[Black "Chigorin Variation 1"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 Closed Spanish- Chigorin Variation"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-masterclass-edition/course/3489, variation/114701"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 
O-O 9. h3 Na5 {Na5 is leads to what is called the Chigorin Variation. It is one 
of three very popular moves in this position. Black forces White's bishop to 
move and prepares c5. The downside is that the knight will be awkwardly placed 
on the edge of the board.} 10. Bc2 {It is important that White does not give up 
his bishop. From c2, the bishop supports the e4-pawn.} c5 {Black expands on the 
queenside and tries to clamp down on the d4-square.} 11. d4 {White plays d4, 
gaining space and creating central tension. This pawn tension in the center is a 
key positional element in the Closed Spanish.} Nd7 {Nd7 is a playable 
alternative to Qc7 but is a bit slow as it does not perpetuate Black's 
development.} 12. Nbd2 {White develops his knight.} exd4 {The central tension is 
released.} 13. cxd4 Nc6 {Black pressures the d4-pawn.} 14. d5 {Now White closes 
up the positon.} Nce5 15. a4 {White's has good play against Black's queenside 
pawns, which can prove to be quite weak if White applies pressure against them.} 
*

