1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 
O-O 9. h3 Na5 {Na5 is leads to what is called the Chigorin Variation. It is one 
of three very popular moves in this position. Black forces White's bishop to 
move and prepares c5. The downside is that the knight will be awkwardly placed 
on the edge of the board.} 10. Bc2 {It is important that White does not give up 
his bishop. From c2, the bishop supports the e4-pawn.} c5 {Black expands on the 
queenside and tries to clamp down on the d4-square.} 11. d4 {White plays d4, 
gaining space and creating central tension. This pawn tension in the center is a 
key positional element in the Closed Spanish.} Qc7 {Qc7 is the most popular 
move, maintaining the central tension and preparing to connect the rooks after 
the light-squared bishop moves.} 12. Nbd2 {White develops his knight. It will 
likely maneuver to g3 or even e3 via f1.} cxd4 {Now BLack releases some of the 
tension in the center with a trade on d4.} 13. cxd4 {Of course White has to 
recapture the pawn.} Rd8 {Instead of improving his minor pieces, Black brings 
his rook to a central file.} 14. b3 {White makes sure that Nc4 does not work.} 
Nc6 15. Bb2 Bb7 {exd4 is also fine.} 16. Rc1 Qb6 17. d5 {Closing the position.} 
Nb4 18. Bb1 {Giving up the bishop is unecessary.} a5 19. Nf1 {White's knight is 
headed for e3.} *

