1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 {Black begins by kicking away the bishop with 
3...a6} 4. Ba4 Nf6 {Black continues his development.} 5. O-O {White castles and 
allows Black to make a choice. Be7 heads towards a Closed Spanish Structure 
while Nxe4 would lead to a more open position.} Be7 {Black places the bishop on 
e7, threatening Nxe4.} 6. Re1 {White guards the pawn with his rook.} b5 {Black 
plays b5 to stop Bxc6 followed by Nxe5 ideas.} 7. Bb3 {The bishop retreats to 
b3.} d6 {7...d6 leads to the Closed Spanish. The alternative is 7...O-O, which 
can either transpose back to a Closed Spanish or become a Marshall Attack.} 8. 
c3 {White prepares to play d4 and creates a square on c2 for his bishop in case 
Black tries to play Na5.} O-O 9. h3 {White prevents the annoying Bg4. Now we 
have arrived in the starting position of the Closed Spanish. Here Black will 
usually choose from Na5, Nb8, or Bb7, all of which are covered in this 
repertoire. White's play in the Closed Spanish is centered around a stronger 
center and undermining Black's extended queenside pawns with moves such as a4 in 
the future.} *

