1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3 
d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 {Black recaptures the pawn.} 10. Nxe5 {White accepts the extra 
pawn.} Nxe5 11. Rxe5 {White is now up a pawn.} c6 {c6 has been found to be the 
best move. Black takes the time to defend his knight on d5 and then play 
actively with his bishops.} 12. d3 {d3 is a key move. This move has developed a 
very good reputation recently. d4 is also playable but Black has very good 
compensation for the lost pawn. In these d3 lines, White will often give back 
the pawn to enter an advantageous endgame.} Bd6 {Attacking the rook.} 13. Re1 
{The rook should simply come back.} Qh4 {Qh4 is the alternative to Bf5. Black 
seeks attacking play on the kingside.} 14. g3 {White has to do something about 
the threat of checkmate.} Qh3 15. Re4 {This is a very cool idea. White wants to 
get rid of the queen with Rh4.} Qd7 {The queen comes back to d7.} 16. Nd2 Bb7 
17. Re1 {If Black's queen is no longer on h3, White's rook no longer serves a 
purpose on e4.} c5 {Black begins to expand on the queenside.} 18. Ne4 {White 
threatens to win the two bishops.} Be7 19. Bg5 {In the endgame, White's 
queenside majority can become very dangerous. Black does not have enough 
compensation for the lost pawn.} *

