1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 {Bc5 is a very 
classical way of handling the position. The bishop quickly becomes a target.} 7. 
c3 d6 {Nxe4 would be incredibly risky as Black's king is still on the e-file.} 
8. d4 {A trade in the center only favors White, who will then have two center 
pawns.} Bb6 9. a4 {White begins to undermine the b-pawn. Now Black has three 
moves to choose from.} Bg4 {Black immediately threatens Bxf3 ideas.} 10. Bg5 
{White also pins the knight.} Rb8 11. axb5 axb5 12. d5 {The position closes} Ne7 
{White is slightly better.} *

