1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bb7 {This is called 
the Archangelsk Variation. Black develops quickly on the queenside.} 7. Re1 {Re1 
is a natural move, lending the e4-pawn some support.} Bc5 8. c3 {White's idea is 
to play d4 with tempo next, asserting that the bishop is misplaced on c5.} d6 9. 
d4 {White plays d4 with tempo, as planned.} Bb6 {The bishop retreats} 10. Be3 
{The bishop supports d4. Nxe4 is not a worry because White can play the simple 
d5.} O-O {Black castles.} 11. Nbd2 {The knight is ready to make the standard 
maneuver to g3.} h6 12. h3 {White stops any Ng4 ideas.} Re8 13. d5 {White forces 
a favorable trade of bishops.} Ne7 14. Bxb6 {The bishops are traded.} cxb6 15. 
Bc2 {The bishop no longer has any role on b3.} Ng6 16. Bd3 {White has good play. 
Nf5 can be met by Bf1 followed by g3.} *

