1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 {Black chooses to enter the Berlin 
endgame. This is a favorite of many top players who are looking to draw with the 
Black pieces. However, the endgame is anything but dry and there are many 
imbalances to consider. I will not provide an in-depth analysis of the Berlin 
endgame in this repertoire because I simply feel I am strong enough of a player 
to really understand the intricacies of this endgame.} 5. d4 {White tries to pry 
open the e-file. Now Black will usually go into the main line of the Berlin with 
Nd6.} Nd6 6. Bxc6 {Now instead of wasting a tempo retreating the bishop, White 
gives up the bishop pair in exchange for structural damage to Black's pawns.} 
dxc6 {Black recaptures the pawn. bxc6 would weaken Black's pawn structure even 
more because more pawn islands have been created.} 7. dxe5 {White wins back the 
pawn.} Nf5 {f5 is the most active square for the Black knight.} 8. Qxd8+ {White 
trades queens and enters an endgame.} Kxd8 {This is the starting position of the 
Berlin Endgame. Some imbalances have been created: White owns a queenside 
majority that later can create a dangerous passed pawn, while Black owns the 
bishop pair but has to deal with structural issues (the doubled c-pawns) .} 9. 
h3 {h3 has been the most popular move in recent years. White maintains a lot of 
flexiblity. Now Black has many different moves to choose from, many of which 
lead to an almost identical computer evaluation. I have therefore summarized 
this endgame by discussing Black's two main plans in this position: he can 
either tuck away his king on the kingside via Ke8 or maneuver it to the 
queenside to tuck the king away on b7.} Ke8 {This is Plan A. The king will run 
to the kingside in search of safety.} 10. Nc3 {White continues his development.} 
h5 {Black tries to play actively on the kingside to stop White from creating a 
passed pawn.} 11. Bf4 {White develops and connects his rooks.} Be7 12. Rad1 {The 
d-file is a nice asset the White has.} Be6 13. Ng5 {Now comes a long theoretical 
variation that highlights the fight between imbalances in this position.} Rh6 
14. g3 {White slowly advances his kingside pawns.} Bxg5 {Giving up the bishop 
pair for concrete reasons.} 15. Bxg5 Rg6 16. h4 {Protecting the bishop.} f6 17. 
exf6 gxf6 18. Bf4 Nxh4 {Black uses the pin on the g-file to grab a pawn on h4.} 
19. f3 {White prevents Bg4.} Rd8 {Offering a rook trade.} 20. Kf2 Rxd1 {The 
rooks come off the board.} 21. Nxd1 {This looks counter-intuitive, but White's 
knight will be better placed on e3 than on c3.} Nf5 22. Rh1 {Hitting the pawn on 
h5.} Bxa2 23. Rxh5 Be6 24. Bxc7 {Material is now equal, but the position is not 
symmetrical. If the game were between two grandmasters, a draw is the most 
likely result. However, White has the more pleasant game due to his greater 
chances of creating a passed pawn. The player with better endgame technique will 
win this game.} *

