1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Bc5 {Bc5 is a classical developing move is 
certainly playable. However, White can achieve a nice advantage my using Black's 
bishop as a target.} 5. Nxe5 {The tactical justification for this move is that 
Nxe5 runs into d4, and the knight and bishop are forked. White wins back the 
piece. Now Black can choose whether to take the knight on e5, or grab the pawn 
on e4 instead.} Nxe4 {Black's second option: grabbing the pawn on e4..} 6. Qe2 
{Qe2 leads to a forcing sequence of moves that favors White.} Nxe5 {Any other 
move would lead to catastrophy for Black because there are tactics along the 
e-file.} 7. Qxe4 Qe7 {Black guards the knight and breaks the pin on the e-file.} 
8. Nc3 Ng6 {Liquidation is the best way for Black to reduce his problems.} 9. 
Qxe7+ {Now Black can recapture in many ways. The endgame favors White for 
dynamic reasons such as development and king safety.} *

