1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5 4. Nc3 fxe4 5. Nxe4 d5 {Play becomes very sharp 
and it is important to play precisely.} 6. Nxe5 {White takes advantage of the 
pin.} dxe4 {Black takes on e4.} 7. Nxc6 {Now Black has to choose between the 
main line Qg5 and also rather popular move Qd5.} Qg5 {Qg5 is the main line. 
Black hits g2 and the bishop on b5.} 8. Qe2 Nf6 9. f4 {The queen is attacked.} 
Qxf4 10. Ne5+ {Forcing c6.} c6 11. d4 {With a discovery on the queen.} Qh4+ 12. 
g3 {The queen has to move again.} Qh3 13. Bc4 {White's bishop eyes f7.} Be6 14. 
Bg5 {White's other bishop jumps into play.} O-O-O 15. O-O-O {The position is 
still sharp.} Bd6 16. Bxe6+ {White goes for a simplification.} Qxe6 17. Qc4 
{White offers another trade because of his stronger pawn structure.} *

