[White "Steinitz Defense 1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "10 Sidelines"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-masterclass-edition/course/3489, variation/114742"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 {The Steinitz Defense is characterized by this 
move d6. It is practically never seen at high levels but a fairly popular weapon 
in club play.} 4. d4 {White should try to open up the center.} Bd7 {Black breaks 
the pin.} 5. Nc3 {White continues to develop and does not take immediate action 
in the center.} exd4 {Black takes on d4, opening the center.} 6. Nxd4 g6 
{Obviously the bishop would be rather useless on e7.} 7. Be3 Bg7 {Nf6 can be 
played first as well.} 8. Qd2 Nf6 9. Bxc6 {Bxc6 is a very interesting idea that 
I found while looking through my database. The idea is to gollow up with Bh6 and 
rid Black of a key defender of the dark squares.} bxc6 10. Bh6 {White has a very 
comfortable position after the trade of dark-squared bishops.} *

[Event "Ruy Lopez: Masterclass Edition"]
[Site "Sidelines"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Steinitz Deferred 2"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "10 Sidelines"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-masterclass-edition/course/3489, variation/114744"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 {Black kicks away the bishop.} 4. Ba4 d6 {This is 
known as the Steinitz Deferred and is very similar to the Steinitz Defense 
except that Black plays a6 before playing d6.} 5. c3 {White should not lash out 
immediately with d4. It is better to prepare this move with c3 in this case.} 
Bd7 {Bd7 is Black's solid option. White can comfortably play d4.} 6. d4 {White 
can comfortably take control of the center.} g6 {In Steinitz set-ups, it is 
common for Black to try to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop because it does 
not have strong prospects on e7.} 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 {White is simply improving 
the position of his pieces.} Nge7 9. d5 {Now White forces Black to trade off his 
good bishop.} Nb8 10. c4 {There is no rush.} O-O 11. Nc3 {White continues his 
development with a good position. Once Black trades light squared bishops, Black 
will be left with a poor dark-squared bishops.} *

[Event "Ruy Lopez: Masterclass Edition"]
[Site "Sidelines"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Steinitz Deferred 3"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "10 Sidelines"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-masterclass-edition/course/3489, variation/114743"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 {Black kicks away the bishop.} 4. Ba4 d6 {This is 
known as the Steinitz Deferred and is very similar to the Steinitz Defense 
except that Black plays a6 before playing d6.} 5. c3 {White should not lash out 
immediately with d4. It is better to prepare this move with c3 in this case.} f5 
{f5 is Black's sharper option. However, White has nothing to worry about if he 
knows what he is doing.} 6. exf5 {White takes the pawn.} Bxf5 7. O-O {If White 
is able to play d4 here, Black's king will be in severe danger.} Bd3 {Black 
tries to stop the d4 move.} 8. Re1 Be7 9. Bc2 {Now the bishops are traded off 
and White can play d4 once again.} Bxc2 10. Qxc2 Nf6 11. d4 {Thematic.} e4 12. 
Ng5 d5 13. f3 {White wants to open up as many lines as possible and not let 
Black close the center.} h6 14. Nh3 O-O 15. Nd2 {White develops and threatens to 
take on e4.} exf3 16. Nxf3 {White can only be better.} *

[Event "Ruy Lopez: Masterclass Edition"]
[Site "Sidelines"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
