[White "Smyslov Variation"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "10 Sidelines"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-masterclass-edition/course/3489, variation/114750"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {This is a very solid line known as the Smyslov 
Variation. White will get a nice edge against it, but it is certainly playable 
for Black.} 4. c3 {White wants to play d4.} a6 5. Ba4 {The bishop drops back.} 
d6 6. d4 {Now White has achieved his ideal center.} Bd7 7. O-O {White castles 
his king.} Bg7 8. Re1 {Now the rook is placed on the e-file, where it belongs.} 
Nge7 9. d5 {We have transposed to a line in the Steinitz Deferred. Now White 
forces Black to trade off his good bishop.} Nb8 10. c4 {There is no rush.} O-O 
11. Nc3 {White continues his development with a good position. Once Black trades 
light squared bishops, Black will be left with a poor dark-squared bishops.} *

[Event "Ruy Lopez: Masterclass Edition"]
[Site "Sidelines"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Cozio Defense"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "10 Sidelines"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-masterclass-edition/course/3489, variation/114747"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7 {The Cozio Defense is another fairly uncommon 
line that allows White to create a nice center with c3 and d4 without having 
anything to worry about.} 4. O-O g6 {Black tries to fianchetto the bishop.} 5. 
c3 {Supporting a later d4 push.} Bg7 6. d4 {White seizes control of the center.} 
exd4 7. cxd4 d5 {This is Black's counterplay attempt. If Black does not play 
this, he will be horribly passive.} 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Re1+ {However, now lines are 
opened towards the Black king.} Be6 10. Bg5 {Taking advantage of the weak f6 
square.} Qd6 11. Nbd2 {The knight is headed for e4.} O-O 12. Ne4 {The knight 
lands on the very nice e4} Qb4 13. Bxc6 {This creates strong structural damage.} 
bxc6 14. Qc1 {White has an easier position to play.} *

